 500 companies, the highest number of any city.[8]</p>\nSwitzerland\n\n<p>The city is considered an alpha+ world city, listed by the GaWC\'s 2008 inventory[9] and ranked fourth among global cities by A.T. Kearney\'s 2012 Global Cities Index.[10] In 2012, Tokyo was named the most expensive city for expatriates, according to the Mercer and Economist Intelligence Unit cost-of-living surveys,[11] and in 2009 named the third Most Liveable City and the World’s Most Livable Megalopolis by the magazine Monocle.[12] The Michelin Guide has awarded Tokyo by far the most Michelin stars of any city in the world.[13][14]\nTokyo hosted the Summer Olympic Games in 1964, and is scheduled to host the games again in 2020.[15]</p>\n\n<p>References <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tokyo\" target=\"_blank\">Wikipedia.org [en]</a></p>','[]','{\"sku\":\"travel-japan-tour-12\",\"slug\":\"travel-japan-tour-12\",\"name\":\"Japan tour for extra-large group\",\"price_including_vat\":false,\"description\":\"<p>Tokyo (\\u6771\\u4eac T\\u014dky\\u014d?, \\\"Eastern Capital\\\") (Japanese: [to\\u02d0k\\u02b2o\\u02d0], English \\/\\u02c8to\\u028aki.o\\u028a\\/), officially Tokyo Metropolis (\\u6771\\u4eac\\u90fd T\\u014dky\\u014d-to?),[4] is one of the 47 prefectures of Japan.[5] Tokyo is the capital of Japan, the centre of the Greater Tokyo Area, and the largest metropolitan area in the world.[6] It is the seat of the Japanese government and the Imperial Palace, and the home of the Japanese Imperial Family. Tokyo is in the Kant\\u014d region on the southeastern side of the main island Honshu and includes the Izu Islands and Ogasawara Islands.[7] Tokyo Metropolis was formed in 1943 from the merger of the former Tokyo Prefecture (\\u6771\\u4eac\\u5e9c T\\u014dky\\u014d-fu?) and the city of Tokyo (\\u6771\\u4eac\\u5e02 T\\u014dky\\u014d-shi?).<\\/p>\\n\\n<p>Tokyo is often referred to and thought of as a city, but is officially known as a \\\"metropolitan prefecture\\\", which differs from a city